China Stocks: Baotou Rare-Earth, China Coal, Huaxin Cement

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-09-20T07:10:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-20/china-stocks-baotou-rare-earth-china-coal-huaxin-cement.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 3 p.m. local time close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, gained 10 points, or 0.4 percent, to
2,447.76. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  added 0.4 percent to 2,689.84.  Cement Stocks: Tangshan Jidong Cement Co. (000401 CH)
climbed 3.4 percent to 15.94 yuan, the most since Aug. 15.
Anhui Conch Cement Co. (600585 CH), China’s biggest cememt
producer, rose for the first time in five days, gaining 1.4
percent to 17.39 yuan.  Cement stocks advanced on speculation demand for the
building material will increase on government plans to support
construction of affordable housing. China will let financial
institutions lend to qualified local government financing
vehicles for public-rental housing projects, the government said
yesterday, citing a meeting presided over by Premier  Wen Jiabao .  China Coal Energy Co. (601898 CH), the nation’s second-
largest coal producer, fell 1.2 percent to 8.91 yuan, extending
yesterday’s 5.9 percent decline. China Coal said it will begin
safety inspections of underground mines in Shanxi. A suspension
of output is “short-term” and won’t have a “material impact”
on the operations of the company.  Inner Mongolia Baotou Steel Rare-Earth Hi-Tech Co. (600111
CH), China’s biggest producer of rare earth, added 1.5 percent
to 56.09 yuan, its biggest gain since Sept. 7. The company plans
to support the price of neodymium praseodymium oxide by buying
the commodity for as much as 900,000 yuan ($140,900) per ton on
the market, Shanghai Securities News reported.  Zijin Mining Group Co. (601899 CH), China’s biggest gold
miner by market value, slid for a ninth day, losing 1.2 percent
to 4.91 yuan. That’s the longest losing streak since August
2008, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. Zijin Mining said
it will pay 1.52 million yuan in “advanced compensation” as
ordered by the People’s Court for deaths and injuries related to
the collapse of a tailing dam last year in Xinyi city, southern
 Guangdong province .  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Shiyin Chen  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
